 Linking Skills Profile
Executive Summary 
5th Edition

The concept of Linking was developed from empirical studies in the 1980s by Drs. Charles Margerison 
and Dick McCann during their research to define work functions. Several activities that correlated 
strongly to form a variable that was eventually defined as 'Linking' were placed at the centre of the 
Types of Work Wheel to indicate their shared relationship with the eight Types of Work. Linking 
was later defined as a set of behaviours that coordinate and integrate teamwork, initially divided 
into People Linking Skills and Task Linking Skills. In 2002, the model was extended to include the 
Leadership Linking Skills of Motivation and Strategy.
